Art,<br><br>
What a strange web all of this is. I believe as you do that this is all a very pretty painted picture. How much is staged we don't know. You are right about the family values, families would accept their warriors and care for them, no matter what side they fought on. Recent uprising over property rights reminds me of the Vietnam we knew oppression under communist aggression. Still the same today.<br><br>
I do believe that what we left behind has helped sustain and give hope to many of the Vietnamese that stayed behind, that is why, Vietnam survived and is today becoming more open, to our form of democracy, because of economic reasons.<br><br>
I have never taken the time to study the overall Buddhists problem, if I remember correctly, they opposed the Diem South Vietnamese government in the beginning because of the government connection with the Catholics. <br><br>
This open opposition caused the South Vietnamese government to come down hard on them, but I'm not too sure if there was a communist/Buddhists connection at that time. What I find ironic, was if I remember correctly, after Diem and his brother were assassinated, communist sympathizers used the occasion to get the Buddhist to rise up against the United States. Ding, if you do, dang if you don't.<br><br>
I can see that Vietnam's Veterans comradship present, as I saw it during our military contact.<br><br>
Found out today, that Battery &quot;B&quot;, 8th Battalion, 4th Artillery (SP), US Army with four 175mm Guns was assigned the mission of general support of our unit during operation Foster, November 13-30, 1967. Was reading our report of artillery support, according to the report both our batteries and the Armt dropped over 11,600 rounds in and around us during that operation. Funny I remember very little of the impact, possibly cause i was eating dirt so often. It was on the 19th when I first realized that the enemy were trying to kill me. The nerve of them.<br><br>

